</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EF0B9D7A420C40132A25C9EC9989D045" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph id="C7A3F8A8C45E1168FF50CA175EDB6F9D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="7F425122E369C112F69DA6E770361109" authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenophytomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1D85849180B1C1FF0938836302A3652B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is primarily north temperate in distribution, with seven exclusively Palaearctic species (mostly Russian), one Holarctic and Jamaican species, and one eastern Nearctic species. The three species with known hosts have all been reared from 
<taxonomicName id="1B128DBFB9140F2D547C253E1A4A99D9" authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
(Boucher 2003).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9838C18863984FC9F01BABDB9E68409A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The single Delmarva species is distinct among other local 
<taxonomicName id="9EFD46000AC7C644C6C4A65C31D1D92B" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Agromyzidae</taxonomicName>
in having three dorsocentrals that strongly decrease in length anteriorly, and there is a mix of characters seen in other 
<taxonomicName id="F01484C6747FAD7DB34C662979CB6755" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ED8ACDF6F5A09750F7907E2AF30A24E9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgenera: the lateral scutellar seta is absent (also seen in 
<taxonomicName id="8095B5E9FA2CA3C3EE158FC721813EA9" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="54D3F038CF4FE702A144C6086F8B3796" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. s.), the first flagellomere has a strong anterodorsal angle (but not produced to a point as seen in 
<taxonomicName id="900D355744C544AE4D35D4933B1E0C6A" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8D3EA6A6E68A340B4AEE3CD49095FEC8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. s.), the lunule is narrow and slightly higher than wide (similar to some 
<taxonomicName id="30AB23208AE2951137C0B511FA34C395" authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Poemyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poemyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8738B049BEA50F1E3BCE251698AFFCF7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Poemyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the body is darkly pigmented. Support for the subgenus is weak and its relationships to other subgenera require investigation (Boucher 2003).
</paragraph>
